{
    "analysis": "Executor summary received: metric/trace/log/error_logs cover the target window 2022-03-20 14:00–14:29 (UTC+8). metric.csv is large (144,252 rows, 59 cmdb_ids, ~1,152 KPIs). trace.csv and log.csv are available. error_logs.csv contains many warning messages from frontend pods around 14:00:00–14:00:10, indicating frontend-level warnings at the start of the window. To localize the two failures we must: 1) detect metric anomalies (using global thresholds per component-KPI), 2) identify faults (consecutive anomalies), and 3) use traces/logs to pick the root cause component and reason. As a first concrete step we should scan metrics for anomalies within the 14:00–14:29:59 (UTC+8) window by computing the global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full available series and flagging points >= P95. Return a compact ranked list so we can narrow candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following (keep outputs compact and limited): 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series in metric.csv. 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 14:29:59 (inclusive) in UTC+8. 3) Mark rows in that window as anomalies when value >= P95. 4) Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and produce a top-20 table ordered by anomaly count, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold. Also return a compact separate list of top-20 cmdb_id (component) ordered by total anomaly_count summed over their KPIs, with columns: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_count, number_of_kpis_with_anomaly, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8. Limit returned rows to at most 20 each." }

{
    "analysis": "We have scanned metrics, traces, and logs and found sustained, high-volume metric anomalies across many components throughout the 14:00–14:30 window. Key signals: shippingservice2-0 shows many KPI series anomalous for all 30 minutes; adservice and adservice2 have the largest aggregated anomaly counts across many KPIs; frontend pods emit repeated warning messages at ~14:00:00–14:00:10; combined per-minute signal shows high sustained anomaly counts with local peaks near 14:15–14:18 and the highest peak at 14:28. At this stage we must perform fault identification: find which component-KPI time series contain consecutive anomaly streaks (not isolated spikes). Persistent streaks will indicate likely faults and their first occurrence times. Compare streak lengths and earliest times across components to separate the two failures (one may start at 14:00 and be sustained; another may start later around the mid/late window). The next step is to detect long consecutive anomaly streaks per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the already-computed global P95 thresholds (use full metric.csv for thresholds) and the incident window. We'll focus on the top components by total metric anomalies to keep outputs bounded.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, restrict attention to the top 12 components by total metric anomaly count from the previous step (adservice, adservice2, frontend2-0, frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, productcatalogservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, cartservice-1, productcatalogservice2-0, adservice2-0). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within those components do: 1) compute global P95 threshold using the full metric.csv series for that (cmdb_id,kpi_name); 2) filter the metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 14:29:59 (UTC+8) and mark rows where value >= P95 as anomaly; 3) identify consecutive anomaly streaks and keep only streaks with length >= 10 minutes; 4) for each kept streak output a compact row (limit to top 200 streaks kept in memory but return only top 20) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, streak_length_minutes, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8 (start of streak), max_value_in_streak, p95_threshold. Additionally, return an aggregated per-component summary (one row per component) listing: cmdb_id, number_of_kpis_with_long_streaks, earliest_streak_timestamp_UTC+8 among its streaks. Limit both returned tables to at most 20 rows each." }

{
    "analysis": "Executor found many long 30-minute anomaly streaks across many components, but most of these are static/startup KPIs where the series value equals its global P95 (false positives under the >=P95 rule). Per-minute aggregates show sustained high anomaly counts across the window with local peaks around 14:15–14:18 and the highest peak at 14:28, while error_logs show frontend warnings concentrated near 14:00:00–14:00:10. At this stage we must filter out static KPIs and focus on KPIs that show significant deviations from their global P95 (breaches >> 50%), which are more likely true resource faults. Identifying KPIs with large breaches will let us find real faults, their start times, and candidate root-cause components for each of the two failures (early window ~14:00 and later peaks ~14:15–14:28).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, restrict to the top 20 components by total metric anomaly count (use the previously seen ranking: adservice, adservice2, frontend2-0, frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, productcatalogservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, cartservice-1, productcatalogservice2-0, adservice2-0, cartservice-0, cartservice2-0, adservice-0, adservice-1, checkoutservice-0, emailservice-0, emailservice-1, emailservice-2). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in these components do: 1) compute global P95 from full metric.csv for that series; 2) within the incident window (2022-03-20 14:00:00 — 14:29:59 UTC+8) compute max_value_in_window and earliest timestamp when value > p95 (strictly greater); 3) compute breach_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95) / max(1e-9, p95) when p95>0, or mark as 'p95_zero' when p95 == 0 and max_value_in_window > 0; 4) keep only series where either (a) p95 == 0 and max_value_in_window > 0, or (b) breach_ratio >= 0.5. Return a compact top-20 table ordered by descending breach_ratio (or p95_zero first), with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, breach_ratio (or tag 'p95_zero'), earliest_timestamp_value_gt_p95_UTC+8. Also return a compact component-level summary (top 20 components) listing for each component: number_of_kpis_with_large_breach, earliest_breach_timestamp_UTC+8 among its KPIs. Limit each returned table to at most 20 rows." }

